Tag <code>0x34</code> is reserved.

Tags <code>0x36</code>–<code>0xFF</code> are reserved.

=====Operator children layout=====

For operators with a fixed number of children, child sub-trees follow the operator tag (and any operator-specific data) in the order specified by the miniscript fragment definition. For variable-arity operators (<code>thresh</code>, <code>multi</code>, <code>sortedmulti</code>, <code>multi_a</code>), the count is given in the operator data and that many children follow.

=====Key references=====

In MD v0, every key position in the bytecode (i.e., a child slot of <code>pk_k</code>, <code>pk_h</code>, <code>pkh</code>, <code>wpkh</code>, <code>multi</code>, <code>sortedmulti</code>, <code>multi_a</code>, <code>tr</code>) MUST be a placeholder reference of the form:

<pre>
  0x32 <index>
</pre>

where <code>&lt;index&gt;</code> is a single byte (0–255) identifying which entry in the BIP 388 key information vector this position uses. Inline keys (raw xpubs, raw pubkeys) are NOT permitted in v0 bytecode. This guarantees that the Template Card encodes the wallet structure without containing any key material.

====Fingerprints block (optional)====

When the bytecode header's fingerprints flag is set, a fingerprints block follows the path declaration (and precedes the tree operators). Its format is:

{| class="wikitable"
! Byte !! Field !! Notes
|-
| 0 || Block tag || <code>0x35</code>
|-
| 1 || Count || Number of fingerprints in this block (must equal the highest <code>@i</code> index in the template, plus 1)
|-
| 2…(2+4n) || Fingerprints || <code>n</code> consecutive 4-byte master key fingerprints, in placeholder index order
|}

When the block is present, fingerprints[i] is the master key fingerprint corresponding to placeholder <code>@i</code>. This allows a recovery tool to verify which seed corresponds to which placeholder before performing derivation.

When the block is absent (the default in v0), recovery tools match seeds to placeholders by trial derivation and xpub comparison, which is computationally trivial for typical wallets.

'''Privacy.''' The fingerprints block leaks which seeds match which <code>@i</code> placeholders. The block is '''optional''' — implementations SHOULD NOT emit it by default. Recovery tools MUST warn the user before encoding fingerprints, especially for solo-user single-seed wallets where the disclosure is unnecessary. Decoders that surface the parsed block to the user MUST flag it as a privacy-sensitive field.

=====Byte-layout example=====

The bytecode for the policy <code>wsh(multi(2, @0/**, @1/**))</code> with fingerprints block <code>[0xdeadbeef, 0xcafebabe]</code> and the BIP 84 mainnet shared path (<code>m/84'/0'/0'</code>, named indicator <code>0x03</code>) is:

<pre>
04 33 03 35 02 deadbeef cafebabe 05 19 02 02 32 00 32 01
</pre>

Annotated:

{| class="wikitable"
! Bytes !! Field !! Decoded
|-
| <code>04</code> || Header || v0; fingerprints flag set (bit 2 = 1)
|-
| <code>33 03</code> || Path declaration || <code>Tag::SharedPath</code> (<code>0x33</code>) + named indicator <code>0x03</code> (= <code>m/84'/0'/0'</code>)
|-
| <code>35 02</code> || Fingerprints block header || <code>Tag::Fingerprints</code> (<code>0x35</code>) + count <code>2</code>
|-
| <code>deadbeef</code> || fps[0] || Fingerprint for placeholder <code>@0</code>
|-
| <code>cafebabe</code> || fps[1] || Fingerprint for placeholder <code>@1</code>
|-
| <code>05 19</code> || Operator path || <code>Tag::Wsh</code> (<code>0x05</code>) + <code>Tag::Multi</code> (<code>0x19</code>)
|-
| <code>02 02</code> || Multi parameters || k = 2; n = 2
|-
| <code>32 00</code> || @0 || <code>Tag::Placeholder</code> (<code>0x32</code>) + index <code>0</code>
|-
| <code>32 01</code> || @1 || <code>Tag::Placeholder</code> (<code>0x32</code>) + index <code>1</code>
|}

The same policy without a fingerprints block (header byte <code>0x00</code>) omits the <code>35 02 deadbeef cafebabe</code> bytes; the surrounding bytes are identical.

====LEB128 encoding====

Unsigned integer fields marked LEB128 (timelock values, threshold and count fields ''when so noted'', explicit-path child numbers) use little-endian base-128 (LEB128) variable-length encoding: each byte holds 7 bits of the integer with the most significant bit set when more bytes follow. The byte order within the LEB128 is little-endian (least significant 7 bits first).

Note: The <code>multi</code>, <code>thresh</code>, etc. threshold and count fields described above use single-byte encoding, not LEB128, because they are bounded by the BIP 388 wallet-policy size limits (≤ 20 keys for segwit v0; ≤ 32 keys for taproot). Implementations MUST reject threshold or count values that exceed the maximum permitted by the surrounding script type.

====Taproot tree====

The <code>tr()</code> operator (<code>0x06</code>) encodes a top-level taproot wallet policy. The internal-key sub-tree (a key reference) immediately follows the <code>tr()</code> tag. If the wallet policy includes a script tree, exactly one tap-leaf miniscript follows the internal-key reference; in v0 the tap-leaf is encoded directly without an intermediate <code>TapTree</code> (<code>0x08</code>) node. The <code>TapTree</code> tag is reserved for v1+ multi-leaf encodings.

A v0 decoder receiving <code>0x08</code> in the tap-leaf position MUST reject the input.

Implementations supporting taproot MUST enforce the per-leaf miniscript subset constraints required by deployed hardware signers (notably Coldcard, which restricts to <code>pk</code>, <code>pk_h</code>, <code>multi_a</code>, <code>or_d</code>, <code>and_v</code>, <code>older</code> — plus the <code>c:</code> and <code>v:</code> wrappers required to spell those operators in canonical BIP 388 form — as of edge firmware). Producing a tap-miniscript wallet policy beyond this subset risks the wallet being unspendable on hardware signers.

=====Byte-layout examples=====

The byte sequences below are the operator-tree portion (everything after the format header byte and the shared-path declaration) for representative v0 taproot policies. The actual encoded policy is <code>[header byte] [shared-path declaration] [operator tree]</code>; the policies shown all use the default header (<code>0x00</code>) and a 2-byte explicit-path declaration <code>33 03</code> (<code>SharedPath</code> tag + length-zero declaration body).

Key-path-only <code>tr(@0/**)</code> — full bytecode <code>00 33 03 06 32 00</code>:

<pre>
  06 32 00
  ^  ^  ^
  |  |  +-- placeholder index 0
  |  +----- Tag::Placeholder (0x32)
  +-------- Tag::Tr (0x06)
</pre>

Single-leaf <code>tr(@0/**, pk(@1/**))</code> — full bytecode <code>00 33 03 06 32 00 0c 1b 32 01</code>:

<pre>
  06 32 00       0c 1b 32 01
  -- internal key   -- leaf miniscript --
                 ^  ^  ^  ^
                 |  |  |  +-- placeholder index 1
                 |  |  +----- Tag::Placeholder (0x32)
                 |  +-------- Tag::PkK (0x1B)
                 +----------- Tag::Check (0x0C)   ; the c: wrapper that BIP 388
                                                   ; emits when expanding pk(K)
                                                   ; under wsh()/tr()
</pre>

Single-leaf <code>tr(@0/**, multi_a(2, @1/**, @2/**, @3/**))</code> — full bytecode <code>00 33 03 06 32 00 1a 02 03 32 01 32 02 32 03</code>:

<pre>
  06 32 00     1a 02 03 32 01 32 02 32 03
  -- internal     -- multi_a(2, @1, @2, @3) --
                  ^  ^  ^  ^^^^^ ^^^^^ ^^^^^
                  |  |  |  |     |     +-- @3 placeholder
                  |  |  |  |     +-------- @2 placeholder
                  |  |  |  +-------------- @1 placeholder
                  |  |  +-- count n=3 (single byte)
                  |  +----- threshold k=2 (single byte)
                  +-------- Tag::MultiA (0x1A)
</pre>

A nested-allowed-operator example combining <code>or_d</code>, <code>and_v</code>, <code>v:</code>, and <code>older</code> — <code>tr(@0/**, or_d(pk(@1/**), and_v(v:older(144), pk(@2/**))))</code> — encodes to full bytecode <code>00 33 03 06 32 00 16 0c 1b 32 01 11 0e 1f 90 01 0c 1b 32 02</code>; the script-tree portion alone is <code>16 0c 1b 32 01 11 0e 1f 90 01 0c 1b 32 02</code>:

<pre>
  16 0c 1b 32 01            11 0e 1f 90 01 0c 1b 32 02
  -- or_d ----              -- and_v -----------------
  ^  -- pk(@1) ---          ^  -- v:older(144) -- -- pk(@2) ---
  |                         |  ^  ^  ^^^^^
  |                         |  |  |  +-- LEB128(144) = 0x90 0x01
  |                         |  |  +----- Tag::Older (0x1F)
  |                         |  +-------- Tag::Verify (0x0E) ; v: wrapper
  +-- Tag::OrD (0x16)       +-- Tag::AndV (0x11)
</pre>

====Round-trip canonical form====

An MD-encoded Template Card MUST round-trip losslessly with the BIP 388 wallet policy string in canonical form. Canonical form requires:

* No optional whitespace anywhere in the policy string.
* Multipath shorthand <code>/**</code> is expanded to <code>/&lt;0;1&gt;/*</code> in canonical form.
* The key information vector is ordered by ascending placeholder index, with <code>@0</code> first.
* Hardened path components use the <code>'</code> character (not <code>h</code> or <code>H</code>).

Encoders MUST produce canonical form. Decoders MUST accept canonical form and SHOULD accept the equivalent non-canonical forms above (normalizing on decode). Decoders MAY reject other non-canonical inputs (e.g., re-ordered key vectors that don't match placeholder indices).

===Chunking===

When a Template Card's canonical bytecode exceeds the maximum payload of a single long-code codex32 string (56 bytes), the encoding MUST be chunked. (The 4-byte cross-chunk integrity hash is appended only when chunking is used; it does not factor into the single-string capacity decision.) Encoders MAY also chunk smaller bytecodes for ergonomic reasons (e.g., to fit on physical media) but SHOULD prefer single-string encoding when the payload fits.

====Cross-chunk hash====

Before chunking, encoders compute a 4-byte cross-chunk integrity hash:

<pre>
  cross_chunk_hash = SHA-256(canonical_bytecode)[0..4]
</pre>

The hash is the first 4 bytes of the SHA-256 of the canonical bytecode (everything from the bytecode header through the end of the tree). The hash is appended to the canonical bytecode, and the resulting byte stream is split into chunk fragments.

Decoders compute the hash over the reassembled bytecode (excluding the trailing 4 hash bytes) and verify it matches the trailing bytes. Mismatch MUST cause the decode to fail with an error specifically identifying the cross-chunk integrity check.

====Chunk format====

Each chunk is a complete codex32-derived string with the chunked Template Card header (type = 1). The total chunk count and chunk index fields in the header determine reassembly order. The wallet identifier (4 chars) MUST be identical across all chunks of one Template Card.

Encoders SHOULD divide the canonical bytecode + hash into chunks of approximately equal size; the exact division is implementation-defined provided each chunk's fragment fits within the chunk's chosen code (regular or long). Decoders MUST accept any valid division.

====Reassembly====

Decoders reassemble a chunked Template Card by:

# Collecting all chunks transcribed by the user.
# Verifying all chunks share the same wallet identifier; reject if mixed.
# Verifying all chunks declare the same total chunk count; reject if inconsistent.
# Sorting chunks by chunk index; reject if any index appears multiple times or is missing.
# Verifying the highest index equals (count − 1); reject if not.
# Concatenating fragments in index order to reconstruct the canonical bytecode plus cross-chunk hash.
# Splitting off the trailing 4 bytes and verifying the cross-chunk hash; reject on mismatch.
# Decoding the resulting canonical bytecode as a Template Card.

===Wallet identifier (Tier 3)===

A Wallet ID is a derived identifier optionally engraved on a separate medium for cross-verifying a digital backup of the policy against the engraved Template Card. The Wallet ID is computed as:

<pre>
  wallet_id = SHA-256(canonical_bytecode)[0..16]
</pre>

The first 16 bytes of the SHA-256 of the canonical bytecode (the same bytecode that is encoded as the Template Card, ''without'' the cross-chunk hash). Wallet IDs are encoded as 12-word BIP 39 mnemonic phrases (128 bits, including a 4-bit checksum word).

A Wallet ID is OPTIONAL and never required for recovery from the Template Card alone. It serves only as a cryptographic anchor for verifying that a supplemental digital copy of the policy is authentic.

===Decoder requirements===

Conformant MD decoders MUST:

# Recognize the MD HRP and reject any other HRP.
# Reject mixed-case strings.
# Reject unknown format-version or card-type values.
# Implement BCH error correction for both regular and long codes per the polynomials specified above.
# Implement erasure-aware decoding when the user supplies known-bad positions.
# Compute the cross-chunk hash over reassembled chunks and reject on mismatch.
# Validate the bytecode against the tag table; reject unknown tags or malformed structure.
# Round-trip with BIP 388 canonical form.

Decoders SHOULD:

# Implement structure-aware candidate filtering during recovery (see "Guided recovery", below).
# Provide informational reporting on every decode attempt.
# Display the bech32 alphabet and example characters during user transcription.

===Decoder reporting===

For every decode attempt, conformant decoders MUST report:

{| class="wikitable"
! Field !! Values !! Notes
|-
| Outcome || clean / auto-corrected / erasure-corrected / structure-aided / failed || Required
|-
| Errors corrected || integer 0–N, with positions || Required when applicable
|-
| Correction method || which technique succeeded || Required
|-
| Verification status || which post-decode checks passed || Required (cross-chunk hash, seed-derived xpub match, blockchain history if performed)
|-
| Confidence || Confirmed / High / Probabilistic / Failed || Required (see "Recovery confidence", below)
|}

A decoder MUST NOT report "Confirmed" confidence unless ALL of:

* BCH decode succeeded with at most 4 errors corrected total
* Cross-chunk hash verified (if multi-chunk)
* All <code>@i</code> placeholders matched user's seeds at recovered paths
* User explicitly confirmed the recovered policy structure matches expectation

Lower confidence levels MUST be reported with specific qualifiers identifying which guarantees did not hold.

===Guided recovery===

A guided recovery flow is REQUIRED in any MD-conformant tool. The flow combines BCH ECC, erasure decoding, user-supplied structural knowledge, and seed-derived xpub verification to recover damaged backups.

The flow MUST proceed through these stages, in order:

# '''Damage assessment.''' Accept the user's transcribed string(s). Display per-position character status. Allow user to mark positions as unreadable (erasures).
# '''Standard decode.''' Attempt BCH decoding with no user input. If successful, report and stop.
# '''Erasure-aware decode.''' If standard decode fails and erasures are marked, attempt erasure decoding (up to 8 erasures per string). If successful, report and stop.
# '''Structure elicitation.''' If decoding still fails, prompt the user for structural information they remember about the policy: wallet kind, key count, threshold, derivation path, timelock values, wallet identifier (if separately stamped).
# '''Constrained candidate search.''' Encode the user's structural assertions as a partial bytecode template. Enumerate candidate codewords within an extended Hamming radius (up to ~12) that decode to valid MD bytecode AND match the user's assertions.
# '''Candidate verification.''' For each surviving candidate, derive xpubs from available seeds at the candidate's declared paths, verify they map to the expected placeholders, verify cross-chunk hash if multi-chunk, and reject candidates failing any check.
# '''Optional blockchain verification.''' With explicit user consent, derive the candidate's first N receive addresses and check on-chain history. Disclose privacy implications before this step.
# '''Result presentation.''' Display the recovered wallet policy in BIP 388 form, the Wallet ID, derived xpubs, and the confidence level per "Decoder reporting".

Tools MUST disclose privacy implications before any blockchain query and SHOULD default to offline operation. Tools MUST NOT transmit recovered policy material to external services without explicit user consent.

==Rationale==

===Why a new format?===

Existing engravable formats (BIP 39, codex32) target seeds (uniformly random fixed-length entropy). Neither has framing for arbitrary structured data, and neither encodes wallet structure. Bytewords / UR encodes descriptors but with weak (CRC32) error correction and verbose output. <code>descriptor-codec</code> compactly encodes descriptors but produces raw bytes designed for QR/NFC, not engraving. No existing format combines a compact descriptor encoding with strong BCH error correction in a hand-transcribable form. MD fills this gap.

===Why codex32-derived encoding?===

Codex32 (BIP 93) is purpose-built for hand-transcribed bitcoin secrets. Its bech32 alphabet excludes visually confusable characters; its BCH polynomials provide strong error correction with mathematically guaranteed bounds; reference implementations exist; the encoding scheme is well-reviewed.

However, codex32's HRP is fixed to <code>ms</code> and its header structure is hard-coded for BIP 32 master seeds (Shamir threshold and identifier fields). Codex32 has no extensibility mechanism for non-seed payloads. MD therefore reuses codex32's '''cryptographic primitives''' (alphabet, BCH polynomials) but defines its own HRP and header structure, treating codex32 as a building block rather than a host format. This is consistent with how BIP 350 (bech32m) reused BIP 173's primitives with a different generator constant.

===Why a new HRP?===

A new HRP (<code>md</code>) is required because:
* Codex32's <code>ms</code> HRP cannot be reused without breaking codex32's seed-payload semantics.
* The bech32 checksum is computed over the HRP, providing domain separation: a damaged MD string cannot be misinterpreted as a bech32 address or codex32 seed share.
* The HRP serves as format self-identification for human readers and parsers.

The two-character HRP <code>md</code> was chosen as a compact, readable abbreviation of "Mnemonic Descriptor". It was verified clean against the SLIP-0173 registry, Lightning HRPs, Liquid sidechain HRPs, Codex32 (<code>ms</code>), Nostr NIP-19 HRPs, and Cosmos chain HRPs prior to adoption.

===Why new target constants?===

The target residue constants <code>T_REGULAR</code> and <code>T_LONG</code> are derived NUMS-style ("Nothing Up My Sleeve") as truncations of <code>SHA-256("shibbolethnums")</code> to 65 and 75 bits respectively, taking the most significant bits of the hash interpreted as a big-endian 256-bit integer.

The string <code>shibbolethnums</code> combines this proposal's working name during early development with the conventional <code>nums</code> suffix used in cryptographic constructions to indicate that the value was chosen via a public hash and not through opaque selection. The string itself is the audit trail: any reader can recompute the SHA-256 and verify that the constants follow from it.

We chose new constants rather than reusing BIP 93's <code>MS32_CONST</code> values for two reasons. First, although the HRP-mixing recipe (BIP 173 <code>hrp_expand</code>) produces residues that differ between any two HRPs sharing this polynomial, picking distinct target constants provides residue-level separation as well: damage that maps an MD string toward codex32-style validity is statistically prevented by the combination. Second, signaling matters — reusing codex32's specific target constant verbatim would invite the misreading that MD is "codex32 with a different HRP" rather than a distinct format that borrows codex32's polynomial.

The constants are reproducible by any SHA-256 implementation:

<source lang="python">
import hashlib
h = hashlib.sha256(b"shibbolethnums").digest()
T_REGULAR = int.from_bytes(h, 'big') >> (256 - 65)  # = 0x0815c07747a3392e7
T_LONG    = int.from_bytes(h, 'big') >> (256 - 75)  # = 0x205701dd1e8ce4b9f47
</source>

===Why descriptor-codec for the bytecode?===

<code>descriptor-codec</code> is a public-domain (CC0-1.0) Rust library that encodes BIP 380 output descriptors using a compact tag-based format with claimed 30–40% size reduction relative to plaintext. Its tag table covers all miniscript fragments and produces deterministic round-tripping bytecode. MD extends this with BIP 388 wallet-policy framing (<code>@i</code> placeholders), shared-path declarations, and a path dictionary, but reuses the underlying tag values for compatibility.

This design choice means: (a) MD does not invent a new bytecode for descriptors that are already correctly handled by an existing public-domain implementation; (b) implementations of MD that wish to also handle inline-key descriptors (a v1+ extension) can do so by adopting the existing reserved tags; (c) the MD extensions MAY be upstreamed into <code>descriptor-codec</code> if the maintainer accepts.

===Why the BIP 388 placeholder framing instead of inline keys?===

The placeholder framing has three advantages over inline keys:

# '''Compactness.''' Each <code>@i</code> reference encodes as 2 bytes vs 78 bytes for an inline xpub. For a 6-key policy, this saves ~456 bytes of bytecode — making the difference between fitting one engraved plate and fitting many.
# '''Separation of structure from key material.''' The Template Card contains zero key material in v0; it can be backed up independently of seeds and xpub cards. Loss or compromise of a Template Card does not compromise key secrecy.
# '''Standard alignment.''' BIP 388 already defines the placeholder framing for hardware-signer wallet-policy registration. Aligning MD's bytecode with BIP 388's framing minimizes work for wallets that already produce BIP 388 wallet policies.

===Why mandate guided recovery in the spec?===

The format's robustness story has two layers: BCH error correction (always present) and structure-aware recovery (when structural knowledge is available). The latter substantially extends the correction envelope but requires implementations to expose it. If guided recovery were optional, different MD tools would offer different recovery success rates for the same damaged input, undermining the format's reliability promise.

By specifying guided recovery as a conformance requirement, all MD tools provide consistent recovery semantics. Users with damaged backups are not at the mercy of which tool they happen to be using.

===Why no compression?===

The format already provides large implicit compression via the placeholder mechanism and tag-based encoding (~40× compression on key material vs inline xpubs; ~10× on operator names vs plaintext). For payload sizes typical of bitcoin wallet policies (≤ 60 bytes), generic compression (LZ-family) yields 5–20% additional savings — offset by dictionary overhead, decompressor complexity, and increased attack surface.

Hardware signers parsing MD-encoded policies (Coldcard, BitBox, Jade, Ledger) have memory and code-size constraints that favor direct opcode interpretation over compressed input. The chunking scheme handles arbitrary lengths, so compression's primary benefit (avoiding chunk boundaries) is moot.

If a future revision identifies compression as worth adding, it should be: (a) a dictionary of common timelock values; (b) an n-of-n implicit-thresh opcode for long <code>and_v</code> chains. Generic LZ on bytecode is not recommended.

===Why no built-in encryption?===

The Template Card contains no key material in v0; it encodes wallet structure. A finder of a Template Card learns the spending policy (e.g., timelock periods, threshold counts, the existence of cosigners) but cannot derive any private keys without also obtaining the user's seed(s).

Encrypting the Template Card is technically straightforward but introduces a new failure mode: loss of the encryption key separate from loss of the seed. Since the Template Card is already useless without the seed for actual fund recovery, the privacy gain from encryption (concealing wallet ''structure'') trades against the recovery risk (now requiring two independent secrets).

A future revision MAY define an optional encrypted Template Card variant. v0 does not include one.

===Why mandatory wallet identifier in chunked cards?===

Without per-wallet identifiers, a user with multiple wallets risks mixing chunks from different Template Cards during reassembly. The 20-bit identifier provides ~1-in-1M discrimination against accidental cross-wallet contamination. Combined with the cross-chunk hash, the false-accept probability for accidental misassembly is approximately 2<sup>−52</sup>, which is negligible in practice.

For single-string Template Cards, no wallet identifier is needed because there are no chunks to confuse.

==Backwards Compatibility==

MD is a new format; there is no prior version to be compatible with.

MD does not conflict with existing standards:

* '''BIP 39 / SLIP 39 / BIP 93 (codex32):''' MD uses a different HRP (<code>md</code> vs <code>ms</code>), so an MD string is never confused with a codex32 seed share. The bech32 checksums are computed over the HRP plus data, providing cryptographic domain separation.
* '''BIP 173 / BIP 350 (bech32 / bech32m addresses):''' MD uses neither <code>bc</code>/<code>tb</code>/<code>bcrt</code> HRPs nor the bech32m generator constant; addresses cannot be confused with MD strings.
* '''BIP 380 (output descriptors):''' BIP 380 descriptors do not contain the <code>@</code> character, so a BIP 380 descriptor cannot be confused with a BIP 388 wallet policy, and neither can be confused with MD-encoded bytecode (which is binary, not a descriptor string).
* '''BIP 388 (wallet policies):''' MD ''encodes'' BIP 388 wallet policies. Round-trip with BIP 388 canonical form is a stated invariant.

MD v0 readers MUST reject MD strings with newer format-version bytes (loud failure; recommend the user obtain a newer MD tool). v1+ readers MUST accept v0 strings (graceful upgrade).

==Test Vectors==

A complete reference test vector suite is provided alongside the reference implementation (see "Reference Implementation", below). Two authoritative vector files coexist; implementations targeting v0.1.0 verify against the schema-1 file, while implementations targeting v0.2.0 verify against the schema-2 file.

