===Schema versioning===

The vector schema follows '''additive evolution'''. <code>schema_version: 2</code> is a strict superset of <code>schema_version: 1</code>; readers MAY ignore unknown fields. The two authoritative files coexist: implementations targeting v0.1.0 SHOULD verify against <code>v0.1.json</code>, while implementations targeting v0.2.0 SHOULD verify against <code>v0.2.json</code>. The schema-1 file is byte-frozen at the v0.1.0 release; future schema versions land in new files (<code>v0.3.json</code> for schema 3, etc.) and never modify earlier locks.

Schema-2 adds three optional fields:

* On <code>Vector</code>: <code>expected_fingerprints_hex</code> — present (as a list of 8-char lowercase-hex strings) for vectors encoded with a fingerprints block, absent otherwise.
* On <code>Vector</code>: <code>encode_options_fingerprints</code> — the raw <code>[u8; 4]</code> values that were passed to <code>EncodeOptions::with_fingerprints</code> when generating the vector, so independent regenerators reproduce the same bytecode.
* On <code>NegativeVector</code>: <code>provenance</code> — a one-sentence note describing how <code>input_strings</code> were generated (e.g., "encoded <code>wsh(pk(@0/**))</code>, then uppercased the data character at position 5"). Implementers MAY consult this field to understand the precise mutation that triggers the named error variant.

===Schema 1 (v0.1.0) contents===

* '''10 positive vectors''' — encode/decode round-trips for the canonical example corpus: single-key (C1), 2-of-3 sortedmulti (C2), 2-of-3 with timelock recovery (C3), 6-key inheritance (C4), 5-of-9 with 2-key recovery (C5), Liana Simple Inheritance (E10), Liana Expanding Multisig (E12), HTLC with sha256 inline hash (E13), Decaying multisig with 6 distinct keys (E14), and a Coldcard-shape representative entry. Each vector pins the input policy, expected canonical bytecode (hex), expected encoded chunk strings, and expected 12-word Tier-3 Wallet ID.
* '''30 negative vectors''' — input strings or scenarios that must be rejected, one per <code>Error</code> variant in the reference implementation. Each vector pins the input plus the canonical name of the expected error variant for cross-implementation matching. (Two of the 30 are placeholder entries for variants whose triggers don't fit the MD-string input shape — <code>EmptyChunkList</code> requires an empty Vec; <code>PolicyTooLarge</code> requires bytecode > 1692 B; both are reachable through the library API but not through a single-string CLI input.) Schema-1 negative <code>input_strings</code> are representative placeholders, not byte-for-byte regenerable from the named error path; the <code>expected_error_variant</code> field is the authoritative cross-implementation contract.

===Schema 2 (v0.2.0) contents===

Schema 2 is a strict superset of schema 1 with the following additions:

* '''14 positive vectors''' — all 10 schema-1 vectors plus 4 new entries:
** <code>tr_keypath</code>, <code>tr_pk</code>, <code>tr_multia_2of3</code> — taproot top-level descriptors exercising the v0.2 <code>tr()</code> + per-leaf subset (BIP §"Taproot tree").
** <code>multi_2of2_with_fingerprints</code> — <code>wsh(multi(2,@0/**,@1/**))</code> encoded with a two-fingerprint block (<code>deadbeef</code>, <code>cafebabe</code>); populates <code>expected_fingerprints_hex</code> and <code>encode_options_fingerprints</code>.
* '''34 negative vectors''' — all 30 schema-1 variants (with <code>input_strings</code> regenerated by per-variant generators that exercise the named error path through the reference decoder; each carries a <code>provenance</code> string) plus 4 new v0.2 entries:
** <code>n_tap_leaf_subset</code> — <code>tr(@0/**, and_v(v:sha256(...), pk(@1/**)))</code>; encoder rejects with <code>TapLeafSubsetViolation { operator: "sha256" }</code> (encode-side; <code>input_strings</code> is empty).
** <code>n_taptree_multi_leaf</code> — bytecode containing <code>Tag::TapTree=0x08</code> in leaf position; decoder rejects with <code>PolicyScopeViolation</code> ("multi-leaf TapTree reserved for v1+").
** <code>n_fingerprints_count_mismatch</code> — encoder rejection when <code>EncodeOptions::with_fingerprints</code> is called with a count that doesn't match the placeholder count; <code>FingerprintsCountMismatch { expected: 2, got: 1 }</code> (encode-side; <code>input_strings</code> is empty).
** <code>n_fingerprints_missing_tag</code> — bytecode header advertises a fingerprints block (bit 2 set) but the byte where <code>Tag::Fingerprints=0x35</code> is expected carries a different tag; decoder rejects with <code>InvalidBytecode { kind: UnexpectedTag { expected: 0x35, got: 0x05 } }</code>.

===Generation and verification===

The vector files are regenerated by:

<source lang="bash">
cargo run -p md-codec --bin gen_vectors -- --output crates/md-codec/tests/vectors/v0.2.json              # schema 2 (default)
cargo run -p md-codec --bin gen_vectors -- --output crates/md-codec/tests/vectors/v0.1.json --schema 1  # schema 1
</source>

…and verified by:

<source lang="bash">
cargo run -p md-codec --bin gen_vectors -- --verify crates/md-codec/tests/vectors/v0.1.json   # schema inferred from file
cargo run -p md-codec --bin gen_vectors -- --verify crates/md-codec/tests/vectors/v0.2.json
</source>

<code>--verify</code> reads the file's <code>schema_version</code> field and dispatches to the matching builder; callers do not pass <code>--schema</code>. The <code>--verify</code> mode does a typed structural compare (not a byte-equal compare), so JSON-formatting drift in <code>serde_json</code> releases doesn't cause spurious mismatches. Both modes are deterministic given the same source code.

Independent implementations SHOULD verify against the committed JSON for the MD version they target. Future schema additions (e.g., property-test vectors, cross-version regression suites) land in new <code>schema_version</code> files; existing locks remain frozen at their release SHA-256.

==Reference Implementation==

The reference implementation is published at [https://github.com/bg002h/descriptor-mnemonic github.com/bg002h/descriptor-mnemonic] and is:

* Written in Rust, building on <code>rust-miniscript</code> (with one upstream patch in flight at [https://github.com/apoelstra/rust-miniscript/pull/1 apoelstra/rust-miniscript#1] for hash-terminal support in <code>WalletPolicy</code>) and the <code>descriptor-codec</code> tag table for compatibility
* Licensed CC0-1.0 to match this specification
* Accompanied by the test vector suite linked above
* Released with the <code>md</code> CLI binary (<code>md encode</code>, <code>md decode</code>, <code>md verify</code>, <code>md inspect</code>, <code>md bytecode</code>, <code>md vectors</code>)

Bindings for Python and TypeScript via standard FFI tooling are planned for v0.2.

